'''Kevin De Bruyne''' ({{IPA|nl|ˈkɛvɪn də ˈbrœynə}}; born 28 June 1991) is a Belgian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{Italian football updater|Napoli}} club [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]] and the [[Belgium national football team|Belgium national team]].<ref>{{cite news |date=12 June 2025 |title=Kevin de Bruyne: Napoli sign former Manchester City midfielder |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cx2q3v2re7go |access-date=12 June 2025 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Widely regarded as one of the greatest players of his generation and one of the best players in [[Premier League]] history, De Bruyne has been described as a "complete" footballer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walsh |first=Euan |url=https://www.givemesport.com/best-footballers-of-the-2020s/|title=10 Greatest Footballers of the 2020s so Far [Ranked]|publisher=GiveMeSport|date=20 June 2024|accessdate=20 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/lists/european-team-2020s-so-far/blt2ca0612a10f97532#cs00e7ba8a53499e5a |title=European Team of the 2020s so far: Robert Lewandowski and Kylian Mbappe make the cut – but no room for Harry Kane, Erling Haaland, Vinicius Jr or Jude Bellingham |website=Goal.com |date=3 January 2025 |access-date=3 January 2025}}</ref><ref name=":6">{{cite web |last=White |first=Mark |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/ranked-the-100-best-premier-league-players-ever/4|title=Ranked! The 100 best Premier League players ever|website=FourFourTwo|date=25 March 2025|access-date=25 March 2025}}</ref>

After spending most of his youth career at [[KAA Gent|Gent]], De Bruyne began his professional senior career at [[KRC Genk|Genk]], where he was a regular player when they won the [[2010–11 Belgian Pro League]]. In 2012, he joined English club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], where he was used sparingly and then loaned to [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]]. He signed with [[VfL Wolfsburg]] for £18&nbsp;million in 2014, establishing himself as one of the best players in the [[Bundesliga]] and was integral in the club's [[2014–15 DFB-Pokal]] win. In the summer of 2015, De Bruyne joined [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] for a then-club record £54&nbsp;million. Making 422 appearances for the club, he won the [[UEFA Champions League]], six Premier League titles, five [[EFL Cup|League Cups]], and two [[FA Cup]]s. In [[2017–18 Premier League|2017–18]], he had a significant role in City becoming the only Premier League team to [[Premier League records and statistics#Points|attain 100 points]] in a single league season. In [[2019–20 Premier League|2019–20]], De Bruyne equalled the record for most assists in a Premier League season and was named [[Premier League Player of the Season|Player of the Season]], the award he won for the second time in [[2021–22 Premier League|2021–22]]. He was again heavily involved in [[2022–23 Manchester City F.C. season|2022–23]], as Manchester City sealed the [[Treble (association football)|continental treble]] in their most successful season to date. In June 2025, he joined [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]] on a free transfer.

De Bruyne made his full international debut in 2010, and he has since earned over 110 [[Caps (football)|caps]], scoring 37 goals for Belgium. He was a member of the Belgian squads that reached the quarter-finals at both the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2016]]. De Bruyne was named in the [[FIFA World Cup All-Star Team|Fan Dream Team]] of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]], as Belgium finished in [[2018 FIFA World Cup#Third place play-off|third place]], as well as appearing at [[UEFA Euro 2020|Euro 2020]], the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]].

De Bruyne has been named in the [[UEFA Champions League#Awards|UEFA Champions League Squad of the Season]] and [[IFFHS World Team#Men's winners|IFFHS Men's World Team]] six times each, [[European Sports Magazines#ESM Team of the Year|ESM Team of the Year]] and the [[FIFPRO World 11]] five times each, the [[UEFA Team of the Year]] three times, and the ''[[France Football]]'' World XI and the Bundesliga Team of the Year once each. He has also won the [[Premier League Playmaker of the Season]] three times, the [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]] twice, [[Manchester City F.C.#Player of the Year|Manchester City's Player of the Year]] four times, the [[UEFA Champions League Best Midfielder|UEFA Champions League Midfielder of the Season]], the Bundesliga Player of the Year, the [[Footballer of the Year (Germany)]], the [[Belgian Sportsman of the Year]] and the [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics#The World's Best Playmaker|IFFHS World's Best Playmaker]] three times each. He was nominated for the prestigious [[Ballon d'Or]] award several times, ending third in the 2022 edition,<ref name=":3">{{cite web |date=17 October 2022 |title=Ballon d'Or 2022 as it happened – Karim Benzema wins Ballon d'Or, Sadio Mane second |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/ballon-d-or/2022/ballon-d-or-2022-karim-benzema-wins-ballon-d-or-sadio-mane-second_sto9185294/story.shtml |access-date=20 October 2022 |publisher=Eurosport}}</ref> and fourth in 2023.<ref name=":5">{{cite web |date=4 November 2023 |title=Result of 2023 Ballon d'Or Top 10 voting points: Messi 462 pts, Haaland 357 pts |url=https://m.allfootballapp.com/news/Headline/Result-of-2023-Ballon-d%E2%80%99Or-Top-10-voting-points-Messi-462-pts-Haaland-357-pts/3214832 |website=All Football}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Genk===
De Bruyne began his career with hometown club KVV Drongen in 1997. Two years later, he joined [[K.A.A. Gent|KAA Gent]] under the guidance of coaches Jan Troos and [[Charly Musonda (footballer, born 1969)|Charly Musonda]]. They focused on his technique: basics, passing, shooting, dribbling. Later in an interview De Bruyne mentioned that their individual coaching had a great impact on his development.<ref>{{Cite web |title=DE STORY VAN KEVIN DE BRUYNE (1) |url=https://boeken.cafe/de-story-van-kevin-de-bruyne-1/ |access-date=22 April 2025 |website=Boeken.café |language=nl-NL}}</ref> In 2005 he moved to [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]], where De Bruyne continued his development in their youth set-up and was rewarded for his progress by being promoted to the first team squad in 2008. From an Interview with his youth club [[K.A.A. Gent|KAA Gent]], it was revealed that De Bruyne was a [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] fan and an admirer of [[Michael Owen]].<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M13079Z9Q88 |title=First ever interview of Kevin De Bruyne ! |language=en-US |access-date=29 March 2026|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201111105516/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M13079Z9Q88 |archive-date=11 November 2020}}</ref>

De Bruyne made his first team debut for [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]] in a 3–0 defeat at [[S. du Pays de Charleroi|Charleroi]] on 9 May 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Charleroi 3–0 Genk|url=http://guardian.touch-line.com/?Lang=0&mTEID=1175&Season=2008%20-%202009&CTID=6&CPID=10&TEID=1175&RFID=&PLID=213148&MAID=408547&ListType=8&pStr=Match_Details&t=2|access-date=27 May 2011|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011114010/http://guardian.touch-line.com/?Lang=0&mTEID=1175&Season=2008%20-%202009&CTID=6&CPID=10&TEID=1175&RFID=&PLID=213148&MAID=408547&ListType=8&pStr=Match_Details&t=2|archive-date=11 October 2012}}</ref> Having established himself in the team [[2009–10 Belgian Pro League|the following season]],<ref name=NFT>{{NFT player|id=39513|name=Kevin De Bruyne|access-date=27 May 2011}}</ref> on 7 February 2010, De Bruyne scored his first goal for the club, which secured all three points for Genk in a 1–0 win against [[Standard Liège]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Genk 1–0 Standard Liege|url=http://guardian.touch-line.com/?Lang=0&mTEID=1175&Season=2009%20-%202010&CTID=6&CPID=10&TEID=1175&RFID=&PLID=213148&MAID=419917&ListType=9&pStr=Match_Details&t=3|access-date=27 May 2011|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011114026/http://guardian.touch-line.com/?Lang=0&mTEID=1175&Season=2009%20-%202010&CTID=6&CPID=10&TEID=1175&RFID=&PLID=213148&MAID=419917&ListType=9&pStr=Match_Details&t=3|archive-date=11 October 2012}}</ref> He scored five goals and made 16 assists in 32 league matches during the 2010–11 season as Genk were crowned [[Belgian Pro League|Belgian]] champions for the third time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Genk clinch third Belgian title with Liege draw|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-belgium-champions-idUKTRE74G7D120110517|work=Reuters|access-date=27 May 2011|date=17 May 2011|archive-date=29 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129184436/http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-belgium-champions-idUKTRE74G7D120110517|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 29 October 2011, De Bruyne scored his first hat-trick for Genk against [[Club Brugge K.V.|Club Brugge]], which ended in a 5–4 win for Genk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.101greatgoals.com/goals/europe/kevin-de-bruyne-3-stars-as-genk-win-5-4-at-club-brugge/|title=Kevin De Bruyne (3) stars as Genk win 5–4 at Club Brugge|access-date=7 July 2014|archive-date=14 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814235138/https://www.101greatgoals.com/goals/europe/kevin-de-bruyne-3-stars-as-genk-win-5-4-at-club-brugge/|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 28 January 2012, De Bruyne scored a brace against [[Oud-Heverlee Leuven|OH Leuven]] in a 5–0 win. On 18 February 2012, De Bruyne scored his first goal back at Genk following his agreed transfer to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and also assisted the other goal in a 1–2 away win against [[RAEC Mons (1910)|Mons]]. De Bruyne ended the season by wrapping up the scoring in a 3–1 victory over [[K.A.A. Gent|Gent]]. He finished the league campaign with eight goals from 28 appearances.

===Chelsea===
[[File:Kevin De Bruyne Chelsea vs AS-Roma 10AUG2013.jpg|thumb|upright|De Bruyne warming up with Chelsea in 2013]]

On 31 January 2012, on the winter transfer deadline day, [[Premier League]] club Chelsea and Genk announced the permanent signing of De Bruyne, with the fee rumoured to be in the region of £7&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news| title = Genk confirm De Bruyne sale| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/7467271/Genk-confirm-De-Bruyne-sale| publisher = Sky Sport| date = 31 January 2012| access-date = 31 January 2012| first = Graeme| last = Bailey| archive-date = 17 December 2018| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181217020217/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/7467271/Genk-confirm-De-Bruyne-sale| url-status = live}}</ref> He signed a five-and-a-half-year contract at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]], but would stay at Genk for the remainder of the 2011–12 season. De Bruyne told the club website, "To come to a team like Chelsea is a dream but now I have to work hard to achieve the level that's necessary."<ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin becomes a blue |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/2594667 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130425091338/http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/2594667 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 April 2013 |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |date=31 January 2012 |access-date=7 July 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Chelsea sign Kevin De Bruyne from Genk| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/16721393| work = BBC Sport| date = 31 January 2012| access-date = 31 January 2012| archive-date = 31 January 2012| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120131175505/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/16721393.stm| url-status = live}}</ref> On 18 July 2012, De Bruyne made his debut for Chelsea in a friendly match against [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS) side [[Seattle Sounders FC]] in a 4–2 win. De Bruyne also played the first half against [[Ligue 1]] giants [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] at [[Yankee Stadium]], New York City.

====Werder Bremen (loan)====
[[File:Kevin de bruyne werder.JPG|thumb|left|upright|De Bruyne during his spell with Werder Bremen in 2012]]

On 31 July 2012, Chelsea announced that De Bruyne was to join [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] in the [[Bundesliga]] on a season-long loan deal.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hytner |first=David |date=31 July 2012 |title=Chelsea's Kevin De Bruyne joins Werder Bremen on season-long loan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/jul/31/chelsea-kevin-de-bruyne-werder-bremen |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200803024759/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/jul/31/chelsea-kevin-de-bruyne-werder-bremen |archive-date=3 August 2020 |access-date=29 March 2026 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Bremen in a 3–2 defeat to [[Hannover 96]] on 15 September, netting from 11 yards out after being played in by [[Eljero Elia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/gamecast/346384/gamecast.html |title=Hannover 96 3–2 Werder Bremen |publisher=ESPN FC |date=15 September 2012 |access-date=7 July 2014 |archive-date=23 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923125859/http://www.espnfc.com/gamecast/346384/gamecast.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/264956/report|title=Huszti is hero and villain|publisher=Sky Sports|date=15 September 2012|access-date=7 July 2014|archive-date=14 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714155023/http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/264956/report|url-status=live}}</ref> He continued his good form, scoring in Bremen's next game, a 2–2 draw with [[VfB Stuttgart]], on 23 September.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/gamecast/346376/gamecast.html |title=Werder Bremen 2–2 VfB Stuttgart |publisher=ESPN FC |date=23 September 2012 |access-date=7 July 2014 |archive-date=15 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215182801/http://www.espnfc.com/gamecast/346376/gamecast.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/267321/report|title=Honours even at Weser Stadion|publisher=Sky Sports|date=23 September 2012|access-date=7 July 2014|archive-date=14 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714170623/http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/267321/report|url-status=live}}</ref> De Bruyne got back on the score sheet on 18 November, scoring the winning goal – despite his team being down to 10 men – as Bremen came from a goal down to defeat [[Fortuna Düsseldorf]] 2–1.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/gamecast/346299/gamecast.html |title=Werder Bremen 2–1 Fortuna Düsseldorf |publisher=ESPN FC |date=18 November 2012 |access-date=7 July 2014 |archive-date=15 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215182846/http://www.espnfc.com/gamecast/346299/gamecast.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/279413/report|title=Winning start for Schaaf|publisher=Sky Sports|date=19 November 2012|access-date=7 July 2014|archive-date=28 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128164311/http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/279413/report|url-status=live}}</ref>

De Bruyne scored his first goal in over two months on 4 May 2013, since netting a consolation goal in [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]'s 6–1 hammering of Bremen, putting his side up 2–0 at home to [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim]] before a late brace from [[Sven Schipplock]] meant that the game finished 2–2.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/gamecast/346123/gamecast.html |title=Werder Bremen 2–2 TSG Hoffenheim |publisher=ESPNFC |date=4 May 2013 |access-date=7 July 2014 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304110032/http://www.espnfc.com/gamecast/346123/gamecast.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/265457/report|title=Hoffenheim fight back to draw|publisher=Sky Sports|date=4 May 2013|access-date=7 July 2014|archive-date=14 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714180310/http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/265457/report|url-status=live}}</ref> He followed this up with a goal in Bremen's next match, securing a place in the Bundesliga for the next season with a 1–1 draw against [[Eintracht Frankfurt]] on 11 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/gamecast/346110/gamecast.htm |title=Werder Bremen 1–1 Eintracht Frankfurt |publisher=ESPNFC |date=11 May 2013 |access-date=7 July 2014 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093152/http://www.espnfc.com/gamecast/346110/gamecast.htm |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/265466/report|title=Eagles secure a point|publisher=Sky Sports|date=11 May 2013|access-date=7 July 2014|archive-date=14 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714155007/http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/265466/report|url-status=live}}</ref>

====Return to Chelsea====
After a successful loan spell in the Bundesliga with Werder Bremen, De Bruyne was linked with a move to stay in Germany with either [[Borussia Dortmund]] or [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]]. Incoming manager [[José Mourinho]], however, assured De Bruyne he was a part of Chelsea's plan for the future, and the player officially returned to Chelsea on 1 July 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=De Bruyne to fight for Chelsea place|url=http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1481782/de-bruyne-fight-chelsea-place?cc=5901|publisher=ESPNFC|date=21 June 2013|access-date=10 August 2013|archive-date=8 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108080625/http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1481782/de-bruyne-fight-chelsea-place?cc=5901|url-status=live}}</ref>

De Bruyne injured a knee while scoring his first goal for Chelsea, in a pre-season friendly game against a Malaysia XI,<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea: Kevin De Bruyne set for scan on knee injury |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/23400115 |first=Richard |last=Conway |website=BBC Sport |date=22 July 2013 |access-date=3 September 2014 |archive-date=9 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209203831/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23400115 |url-status=live }}</ref> but was fit to make his competitive debut on the opening day of the [[2013–14 Premier League]] season against [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], and made an assist for the first goal in a 2–0 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/aug/18/chelsea-hull-city-premier-league |title=José Mourinho enjoys stylish return as Chelsea cruise against Hull |first=Daniel |last=Taylor |newspaper=The Guardian |date=18 August 2013 |access-date=3 September 2014 |archive-date=12 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612211000/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/aug/18/chelsea-hull-city-premier-league |url-status=live |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

===Wolfsburg===
====2013–14 season====
On 18 January 2014, [[VfL Wolfsburg|Wolfsburg]] signed De Bruyne for a fee of £18&nbsp;million (€22&nbsp;million).<ref>{{Cite news |last=Association |first=Press |date=18 January 2014 |title=Chelsea sell Kevin De Bruyne to Wolfsburg |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jan/18/chelsea-sell-kevin-de-bruyne-wolfsburg |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106031122/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jan/18/chelsea-sell-kevin-de-bruyne-wolfsburg |archive-date=6 November 2018 |access-date=29 March 2026 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 25 January 2014, he made his debut for Wolfsburg in a 3–1 home loss against [[Hannover 96]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/wolfsburg/team-news/team-news-de-bruyne-straight-in-for-wolfsburg_132637.html |title=Team News: Kevin de Bruyne straight in for Wolfsburg |work=Sports Mole |date=25 January 2014 |access-date=7 July 2014 |archive-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618130025/https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/wolfsburg/team-news/team-news-de-bruyne-straight-in-for-wolfsburg_132637.html |url-status=live }}</ref> On 12 April 2014, De Bruyne assisted 2 goals in their 4–1 home win against [[1. FC Nürnberg]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoscored.com/Matches/724028/Live/Germany-Bundesliga-2013-2014-Wolfsburg-Nurnberg |title=Wolfsburg-Nurnberg Live |work=Whoscored.com |access-date=7 July 2014 |archive-date=29 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129080041/https://www.whoscored.com/Matches/724028/Live/Germany-Bundesliga-2013-2014-Wolfsburg-Nurnberg |url-status=live }}</ref> After a week he scored his first goal for Wolfsburg in 3–1 away win against [[Hamburger SV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/liga/news/2013/0000291918.php |title=De Bruyne: 'We want nine points' |publisher=Bundesliga |date=20 April 2014 |access-date=7 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422233138/http://www.bundesliga.com/en/liga/news/2013/0000291918.php |archive-date=22 April 2014 }}</ref> He also scored in the last two matches of the [[2013–14 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] helping his team to win against [[VfB Stuttgart]] and [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]].

====2014–15 season====
[[File:2014-10-26 Wolfsburg07 (15669411695).jpg|thumb|De Bruyne playing for Wolfsburg against [[Mainz 05|Mainz]] in 2014]]

De Bruyne scored his first goal of the [[2014–15 VfL Wolfsburg season|2014–15 season]] on 2 October 2014, volleying in a clearance from outside the box to salvage a 1–1 draw against [[LOSC Lille Métropole|Lille]] in the [[2014-15 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/0257-0def869751c4-1379e300168b-1000--wolfsburg-rally-to-peg-back-losc/ |title=Wolfsburg rally to peg back LOSC |publisher=UEFA |date=2 October 2014 |access-date=3 October 2014 |archive-date=3 October 2014 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20141003205743/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000587/match=2014469/postmatch/report/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In the third group match away to [[FC Krasnodar|Krasnodar]] on 23 October, De Bruyne scored twice as Wolfsburg secured their first win in the competition with a 4–2 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/el/news/2014/0000305024.php |title=De Bruyne Double Fires Wolfsburg to First European Win |work=Bundesliga |date=23 October 2014 |access-date=23 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101165628/http://www.bundesliga.com/en/el/news/2014/0000305024.php |archive-date=1 November 2014}}</ref> On 30 January 2015, he scored another brace in a 4–1 home win against [[Bayern Munich]], their first Bundesliga defeat since April 2014.<ref name="VfL Wolfsburg 4 1 Bayern Mun">{{cite news|last1=Begley|first1=Emlyn|title=VfL Wolfsburg 4–1 Bayern Munich|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/30991047|access-date=17 March 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=30 January 2015|archive-date=20 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220135834/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/30991047|url-status=live}}</ref> On 1 March 2015, De Bruyne assisted three goals in a 5–3 win over his former club [[Werder Bremen]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Werder Bremen 3–5 VfL Wolfsburg |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/sport/match/540771.html |publisher=ESPN (UK) |date=1 March 2015 |access-date=17 March 2015 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321175836/http://www.espn.co.uk/football/sport/match/540771.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 12 March 2015, De Bruyne scored two goals in a 3–1 first leg Europa League round of 16 victory over [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/0253-0d804a13c2bf-a8774397b62f-1000--de-bruyne-powered-wolfsburg-snap-back-at-inter/|title = De Bruyne-powered Wolfsburg snap back at Inter|publisher = UEFA|date = 12 March 2015|access-date = 15 March 2015|archive-date = 13 November 2018|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181113001907/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000589/match=2014610/postmatch/report/index.html#de+bruyne+unpicks+inter|url-status = live}}</ref> On 15 March 2015, he scored one goal and assisted another two in 3–0 victory over [[SC Freiburg]].<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/31875612|title = VfL Wolfsburg 3–0 Sport-Club Freiburg|date = 15 March 2015|access-date = 17 March 2015|work = BBC Sport|archive-date = 24 September 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924222335/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/31875612|url-status = live}}</ref>

De Bruyne ended the league season with 10 goals and 21 assists, the latter a new [[Bundesliga records#Assists|Bundesliga record]], as Wolfsburg finished second in the [[2014–15 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] and qualified for the [[2015–16 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rtbf.be/sport/football/etranger/allemagne/detail_de-bruyne-entre-dans-l-histoire-de-la-bundesliga?id=8982166|title=De Bruyne entre dans l'histoire de la Bundesliga|language=fr|date=16 May 2015|work=RTBF Sport|access-date=31 May 2015|archive-date=23 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723093237/https://www.rtbf.be/sport/football/etranger/allemagne/detail_de-bruyne-entre-dans-l-histoire-de-la-bundesliga?id=8982166|url-status=live|trans-title=De Bruyne makes Bundesliga history}}</ref>{{Cref2|N1}} On 30 May 2015, he started and scored in the [[2015 DFB-Pokal Final]] as ''Die Wölfe'' defeated [[Borussia Dortmund]] 3–1 at the [[Olympiastadion (Berlin)|Olympiastadion]] in Berlin.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32938029|title=Borussia Dortmd 1–3 VfL Wolfsburg|date=30 May 2015|work=BBC Sport|access-date=14 February 2018|archive-date=24 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924223916/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32938029|url-status=live}}</ref>

De Bruyne ended his break-out season with 16 goals and 27 assists in all competitions,<ref name=":4">{{cite web|title='Kevin De Bruyne is off to Man City' says Wolfsburg director Klaus Allofs|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/2585622/kevin-de-bruyne-is-off-to-manchester-city-says-wolfsburg|publisher=[[ESPN]]|access-date=28 August 2015|date=28 August 2015|archive-date=10 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810072559/http://www.espn.com/soccer/story/2585622/kevin-de-bruyne-is-off-to-manchester-city-says-wolfsburg|url-status=live}}</ref> and was named the 2015 [[Footballer of the Year (Germany)|Germany Footballer of the Year]].<ref name="Sporza">{{cite web|title=De Bruyne is Speler van het Jaar volgens Duitse Journalisten|url=http://sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/buitenland/Duitsland/1.2400701|date=26 July 2015|work=[[Sporza]]|language=nl|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716195857/http://sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/buitenland/Duitsland/1.2400701|archive-date=16 July 2016|access-date=26 July 2015|trans-title=De Bruyne is Player of the Year according to German journalists}}</ref>

====2015–16 season====
De Bruyne began the season by winning the [[2015 DFL-Supercup]] against [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], providing the cross for [[Nicklas Bendtner]]'s 89th-minute equaliser for a 1–1 draw and then scoring in the subsequent [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]].<ref name=supercup>{{cite news|last1=Dunbar|first1=Ross|title=Bendtner leads Wolfsburg over Bayern Munich on penalties in German Super Cup clash|url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/bendtner-leads-wolfsburg-over-bayern-munich-on-penalties-in-german-super-cup-clash-080115?vid=null|access-date=3 August 2015|work=Fox Sports|date=1 August 2015|archive-date=3 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703050953/https://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/bendtner-leads-wolfsburg-over-bayern-munich-on-penalties-in-german-super-cup-clash-080115?vid=null|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 August 2015, he continued his good form by scoring his first goal of the season, and providing two assists in a 4–1 win at [[Stuttgarter Kickers]] in the first round of the [[2015–16 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=De Bruynes artwork rewarded wide awake Wolves|url=https://www.kicker.de/stg-kickers-gegen-wolfsburg-2015-dfb-pokal-2841065/spielbericht|publisher=Kicker|access-date=10 August 2015|date=8 August 2015|archive-date=23 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190523203751/https://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/dfbpokal/spielrunde/dfb-pokal/2015-16/1/2841065/spielbericht_stuttgarter-kickers-26_vfl-wolfsburg-24.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

In August, in the midst of transfer speculation, De Bruyne said that he would not force Wolfsburg to sell him, but also said that he could not ignore interest from [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], saying: "If an offer does come, I will hear about it and how much it is, but I have not yet heard anything... I would not go to England just to prove that I can play there. I do not have to go to England... If I go there it's because for me and for my family it is a good choice. That's the key for me."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2892/transfer-zone/2015/08/03/14113752/de-bruyne-i-will-not-force-wolfsburg-to-sell-me |title=Manchester City transfer news: Kevin De Bruyne: I will not force Wolfsburg to sell me |work=Goal (website) |date=3 August 2015 |access-date=10 August 2015 |archive-date=15 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215182807/https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2892/transfer-zone/2015/08/03/14113752/de-bruyne-i-will-not-force-wolfsburg-to-sell-me |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 10 August, it was reported that Manchester City had made a second bid for De Bruyne worth £47&nbsp;million. Wolfsburg sporting director, [[Klaus Allofs]], said the club would fight to keep him, saying "I think some other clubs have definitely turned Kevin's head... Some huge figures are doing the rounds and I can understand why Kevin is leaving everything open."<ref>{{cite news |last=Jackson |first=Jamie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/aug/10/kevin-de-bruyne-manchester-city-wolfsburg-47m |title=Manchester City make second bid of £47m for Wolfsburg's Kevin De Bruyne |work=The Guardian |date=10 August 2015 |access-date=10 August 2015 |archive-date=15 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215182802/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/aug/10/kevin-de-bruyne-manchester-city-wolfsburg-47m |url-status=live }}</ref> On 27 August, it was reported that City had made a further bid for De Bruyne worth £58&nbsp;million. Klaus Allofs said that City had made an "astonishing" wage offer to De Bruyne.<ref>{{cite news |title = Kevin de Bruyne: Man City offer 'astonishing' wages |url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34081920 |website = BBC Sport |date = 27 August 2015 |access-date = 27 August 2015 |archive-date = 30 August 2015 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150830000612/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34081920 |url-status = live }}</ref>

===Manchester City===
====2015–16 season====
[[File:Kevin De Bruyne (24640482031) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|De Bruyne playing for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in January 2016]]

On 30 August 2015, Manchester City announced the arrival of De Bruyne on a six-year contract, for a reported club-record fee of £55&nbsp;million (€75&nbsp;million), making him the second most expensive transfer in British football history after [[Ángel Di María]]'s move to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/Team-news/2015/August/Kevin-De-Bruyne-signs-for-Manchester-City/1440878814 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150831144344/http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/Team-news/2015/August/Kevin-De-Bruyne-signs-for-Manchester-City/1440878814 |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 August 2015 |title=Kevin De Bruyne signs for Manchester City |date=30 August 2015 |access-date=30 August 2015 |publisher=Manchester City FC }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Man City sign midfielder De Bruyne |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33686731 |website=BBC Sport |date=30 August 2015 |access-date=30 August 2015 |archive-date=2 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150902015440/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33686731 |url-status=live }}</ref> He made his debut for the team in the Premier League on 12 September against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], replacing the injured [[Sergio Agüero]] in the 25th minute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Premier League leaders Manchester City continued their 100% start to the season with an injury-time winner over Crystal Palace.|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34160754|access-date=14 September 2015|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=12 September 2015|archive-date=21 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121121840/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34160754|url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 September, he scored his first goal for the club against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in first half stoppage time in an eventual 2–1 loss.<ref>{{cite news |first=JJ |last=Bull |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/football-live-blogs/11874291/Manchester-City-vs-West-Ham-United-live.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/football-live-blogs/11874291/Manchester-City-vs-West-Ham-United-live.html |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Manchester City vs West Ham United: as it happened |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=20 September 2015 |access-date=20 September 2015}}{{cbignore}}</ref> He went on to score in a 4–1 [[2015–16 Football League Cup|League Cup]] win against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], on 22 September<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34253381 |title=Sunderland 1–4 Manchester City |website=BBC Sport |date=22 September 2015 |access-date=23 September 2015 |archive-date=20 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120172646/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34253381 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a 4–1 loss to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in the Premier League on 26 September.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/tottenham-hotspur-v-manchester-city-10138638 |title=Recap: Spurs hit four after De Bruyne puts Blues ahead |work=Manchester Evening News |date=26 September 2015 |access-date=28 September 2015 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321175802/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/recap-spurs-hit-four-after-10138638 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 3 October, he scored in the team's 6–1 win against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Bevan |first=Chris |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34366600 |title=Manchester City 6–1 Newcastle United |website=BBC Sport |date=3 October 2015 |access-date=28 January 2016 |archive-date=26 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126134512/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34366600 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 2 October, De Bruyne was announced as one of the players on the longlist for the prestigious [[FIFA Ballon d'Or]] award, alongside teammates Agüero and [[Yaya Touré]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/ballon-dor-list-leaked-fifa-10180903 |title=Ballon d'Or shortlist: Eight Manchester-based players in running for award |work=Manchester Evening News |date=2 October 2015 |access-date=28 January 2016 |archive-date=23 January 2016 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20160123213236/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/ballon-dor-list-leaked-fifa-10180903 |url-status=live }}</ref> Just 18 days later, on 20 October he was revealed by [[FIFA]] as one of the players on the 23-man shortlist for the Ballon d'Or.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34578624 |title=Ballon d'Or: Ronaldo & Messi joined by Aguero & Toure on list |website=BBC Sport |date=20 October 2015 |access-date=28 January 2016 |archive-date=21 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151221102309/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34578624 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 21 October, De Bruyne scored an injury-time winner against [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the [[2015–16 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], to take City within one point of group leaders [[Juventus FC|Juventus]], with three games remaining.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Taylor |first=Daniel |date=21 October 2015 |title=Kevin De Bruyne's late strike earns Manchester City victory over Sevilla |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/oct/21/manchester-city-sevilla-champions-league-match-report |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215182759/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/oct/21/manchester-city-sevilla-champions-league-match-report |archive-date=15 December 2019 |access-date=29 March 2026 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 1 December, he scored a brace in a 4–1 win over [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] to send Manchester City through to the semi-finals of the Football League Cup.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Taylor |first=Daniel |date=1 December 2015 |title=Kevin De Bruyne hits double as Manchester City send Hull packing |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/dec/01/manchester-city-hull-city-capital-one-cup-match-report |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215182803/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/dec/01/manchester-city-hull-city-capital-one-cup-match-report |archive-date=15 December 2019 |access-date=29 March 2026 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

On 27 January 2016, De Bruyne scored a goal in a League Cup semi-final 3–1 victory over [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], but sustained an injury to his right knee that would keep him out of the team for two months.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35425113 |title=Kevin de Bruyne: Man City midfielder set for 10 weeks out |work=BBC Sport |access-date=28 January 2016 |archive-date=28 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628233831/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35425113 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 2 April, De Bruyne made his return from injury in a 4–0 win against [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] at [[Dean Court]], scoring the team's second goal in the twelfth minute.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Aarons |first=Ed |date=2 April 2016 |title=Manchester City's Kevin De Bruyne inspires thrashing of Bournemouth |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/apr/02/bournemouth-manchester-city-premier-league-match-report |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617212930/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/apr/02/bournemouth-manchester-city-premier-league-match-report |archive-date=17 June 2019 |access-date=29 March 2026 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Four days later, he scored the opening goal in a 2–2 draw with [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] in the [[2015–16 UEFA Champions League knockout phase#Quarter-finals|UEFA Champions League quarter-final]] first-leg at the [[Parc des Princes]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/04/06/psg-2-man-city-2-fernandinho-and-kevin-de-bruyne-give-city-cause/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/04/06/psg-2-man-city-2-fernandinho-and-kevin-de-bruyne-give-city-cause/ |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=PSG 2 Man City 2: Fernandinho and Kevin de Bruyne give City cause to dream in Champions League|date=6 April 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph}}{{cbignore}}</ref> On 12 April, De Bruyne scored the winning goal against Paris Saint-Germain, advancing Manchester City to the Champions League semi-finals, for the first time in the club's history, on an aggregate score of 3–2. Writing in ''[[The Independent]]'', Mark Ogden said, "It was a stunning goal from the Belgian, who took a touch to control the ball before curling it beyond [[Kevin Trapp]] from the edge of the penalty area."<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Ogden |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/manchester-city-vs-psg-match-report-kevin-de-bruyne-stars-as-slick-city-charge-to-semi-final-a6981596.html |title=Manchester City vs PSG match report: Kevin De Bruyne stars as slick City charge to semi-final |work=The Independent |date=12 April 2016 |access-date=12 April 2016 |archive-date=13 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413131814/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/manchester-city-vs-psg-match-report-kevin-de-bruyne-stars-as-slick-city-charge-to-semi-final-a6981596.html |url-status=live }}</ref> De Bruyne's next goal came on 8 May in a 2–2 draw with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], although the result left City's Champions League qualification hopes out of their own hands.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36180831|title=Manchester City 2–2 Arsenal|website=BBC Sport|date=8 May 2016|access-date=8 May 2016|archive-date=18 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618014308/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36180831|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2016–17 season====
